         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Beaumont ¶ 30 June 1865 ¶ Dear Sir ¶  ¶ On receipt of your note of the 7th Inst stating that the City Council would be glad of some Plantane trees (platanus orientalis) if procurable from Europe, I wr...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">M65.06.30</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">Samuel Davenport to [William Hughes]</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">No. 35, ACC incoming correspondence, State Library of South Australia, Adelaide.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-weight: bold; ">To proof.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
               <note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-weight: bold; ">Letter emailed to Roger Spencer July 2003. All of this needs to be checked.</seg>
                  </p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-weight: bold; ">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>The correspondent is assumed to be the Town Clerk, W. A Hughes.</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="color: #c00000; font-weight: bold; ">If we decide to keep this as a selected letter, then this note can be expanded using the information from SA Register</seg>
                     <seg style="color: #c00000; ">. </seg>
                     <seg style="color: #c00000; font-weight: bold; ">Note Francis was dismissive. Also interesting that the Council sensible decided to minimise risk of loss by not entrusting all of them to their gardener.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>Beaumont</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">30 June 1865</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>On receipt of your note of the 7th Inst stating that the City Council would be glad of some Plantane trees (platanus orientalis) if procurable from Europe, I wrote to Dr Mueller,<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Letter not found.</p>
               </note> of the Botanic Gardens, Melbourne, inquiring if this tree was yet in his possession.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In reply<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Letter not found.</p>
               </note> I have received the tree itself — of which Dr Mueller begs the acceptance by the Corporation. Dr Mueller adds that he […]<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-weight: bold; ">part of MS missing - ditto below.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> established the first Avenue […] in Austalia. I may state […] the Plantane tree is <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">the</hi>
               </seg> tree of all […] others selected in the South of Europe for shade in the Streets </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="">
                  <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               </seg>Squares of the towns, and in Avenue plantations along the public roads. It has some resemblance to good specimens of the English Lime tree. It bears an amount of pruning, even to cutting down a full grown tree to a mere pillar.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Dr Mueller says it grows with great rapidity </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="">
                  <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               </seg>may be multiplied <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">by cuttings even in the open air</hi>
               </seg>.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>50 plants are now sent </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="">
                  <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               </seg>Dr Mueller very kindly and liberally hopes to be able to send 50 more.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">I am Dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Yours Truly</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Samuel Davenport</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="extra%20space"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 7pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <ref target="https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/39119540"
                    rend="Internet%20link"
                    style="color: #0563c1; ">
                  <seg rend="Internet%20link" style="color: #0563c1; ">
                     <seg style="font-weight: bold; ">South Australian Register</seg>
                  </seg>
               </ref>
               <seg style="color: #c00000; font-weight: bold; "> 6 June 1865, p. 3, report of Municipal Council <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>mtg 5 June(uncorrected OCR)</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="extra%20space"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 7pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="background-color: #ffff00; ">A letter was read from Mr. G. W. Francis, in reply to one from the Town Clerk relating to the introduction of the plan tain-tree for planting along the streets, and stating his opinion that the tree in question would not he the most suitable for the purpose, as there was one in the Botanic Garden which did not prosper very welL</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="extra%20space"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 7pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="background-color: #ffff00; ">
                  <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               </seg>
               <seg style="background-color: #ffff00; ">Mr. Buik remarked that the Hon. S. Davenport was so confident that the tree wauld prosper in the colony that he had offered to import some at his own expense.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="extra%20space"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 7pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="background-color: #ffff00; ">
                  <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               </seg>
               <seg style="background-color: #ffff00; ">On the motion of Mr. Bundey/, seconded by Mr. Murphy, it was decided to accept the Hon. S. Davenport's otter with thanks.</seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="extra%20space"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 7pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <ref target="https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/41034726https:/trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/41034726"
                    rend="Internet%20link"
                    style="color: #0563c1; ">
                  <seg rend="Internet%20link" style="color: #0563c1; ">
                     <seg style="font-weight: bold; background-color: #ffff00; ">South Australian Register</seg>
                  </seg>
               </ref>
               <seg style="background-color: #ffff00; "> 4 July <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>1865, p. 3, report of Municipal Council mtg 3 July</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="extra%20space"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 7pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="background-color: #ffff00; ">The Hon. S. Davenport wrote, stating that he had received from Dr. Mueller, of Melbourne, some valuable information respecting the plantain-tree which had been introduced into Victoria, and suc cessfully cultivated in the Melbourne Botanic Garden. It was a very useful and ornamental tree, suited to the climate, and admirably adapted for planting in public localities Dr. Mueller had sent 50 plants as a donation to the Ritv</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="extra%20space"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 7pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="background-color: #ffff00; ">. A vote of thanks to Mr. Davenport and Dr. Mueller for the donation was passed.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="extra%20space"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 7pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="background-color: #ffff00; ">
                  <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>The Town Clerk stated that the plants hod been handed over to the City Gardener, two of them having been reserved for Mr. Davenport</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="extra%20space"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 7pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="background-color: #ffff00; ">
                  <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Mr. Clark suggested that some others should be reserved. If they were all planted in the city enclosures they might not live, whereas by distri buting a few of them there would be a greater pro bability of some of them being preserved. He moved that the Town Clerk be instructed to dis tribute 20 of the trees to such of the citizens as applied for them, and who would engage to attend to their cultivation.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="extra%20space"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 7pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="background-color: #ffff00; ">
                  <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>The Mayor suggested that some of the trees should be distributed amongst those who might apply for them in the order of priority of appli cations.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="extra%20space"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 7pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="background-color: #ffff00; ">
                  <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Mr. Rankin asked if the tree was the same as that known in England as the plane-tree. If so, it would be a very useful tree for shade and orna ment.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="extra%20space"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 7pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="background-color: #ffff00; ">
                  <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>The Town Clerk replied that it was.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="extra%20space"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 7pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="background-color: #ffff00; ">
                  <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>It was resolved that the Town Clerk be instructed to distribute 20 of the trees in the order of the application to such of the citizens as would engage to cultivate thenL</seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
         </div>
